US Media_Apr22

First we install the relevant libraries.

Then we load them

We load the data that has been pre-processed in Python. Words with a frequency less than 3 were also removed from the corpus.

# set working directory
datadir <- "C:/Users/analo/OneDrive - University of Glasgow/University of Glasgow/Amsterdam Visit/Voter-ID-US-News-Media/Descriptives/"
df <- readtext(paste0("preprocessed.csv"), text_field = "title")

Then we create the corpus

corpus <- corpus(df)

We create a tokens object. tokens() segments texts in a corpus into tokens (words or sentences) by word boundaries. By default, tokens() only removes separators (typically whitespaces).

tokens <- tokens(corpus, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_symbols = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE)%>%
  tokens_compound(pattern = phrase(c('U S', 'united_states')))%>%
  tokens_select(pattern = c("advertisement", "u"), selection = "remove")%>%
  tokens_replace(c("id"), c("identification"))%>%
  tokens_replace(c("U_S"), c("united_states"))%>%
  tokens_group(groups = ideology) %>%
  tokens()

tokens <- tokens_select(tokens, pattern = stopwords("en"), selection = "remove")

Then we create a dataframe object

dfm <- dfm(tokens)

Top words

We plot top features:

freq <- textstat_frequency(dfm, n = 20)
ggplot(data = freq, aes(x = nrow(freq):1, y = frequency)) +
geom_point() +
facet_wrap(~ group, scales = "free") +
coord_flip() +
scale_x_continuous(breaks = nrow(freq):1,
labels = freq$feature) +
labs(x = NULL, y = "word frequency")

Wordcloud by ideology

We plot top features by media ideology:

wordcloud_dfm_comp<-dfm_group(dfm, groups = ideology)
textplot_wordcloud(dfm_trim(wordcloud_dfm_comp, min_termfreq = 15, max_words = 40), comparison = TRUE, color = c("blue", "red"))

KWIC

We use KWIC to explore words of interest:

kwic(tokens, pattern = "all-star", valuetype = "glob", window = 3)[3]
## Keyword-in-context with 1 match.                                                                    
##  [left, 10802] MLB's decision move | All-Star | Game Georgia million

Keyness analysis

A keyness analysis is then conducted to identify which words are more frequently used by right leaning media when covering voter ID compared to left leaning media. Keyness is a statistical index used to evaluate how significant a word is to a document. The statistical significance of the frequency difference is reported through Chi-Squared values. Positive values mean that the keyword appears more often than would be expected by chance in comparison with the reference corpus (i.e. left leaning news media stories). Likewise, a word which is negatively key occurs less often than would be expected.

# Calculate keyness 
result_keyness <- textstat_keyness(dfm, target = 1L , measure = c("chi2"),sort = TRUE)
textplot_keyness(result_keyness, labelsize = 4,labelcolor = "black", color = c("blue", "red"), min_count = 20, n = 25)
